BikeSack

Class RangeInstrument

  • Object
    • Instrument
      • RangeInstrument

  • public class RangeInstrument
extends Instrument

    Bike Sack RangeInstrument extends BikeSack's abstract 'Instrument' and allows for an instrument with a proportional value. It can also display a selective range to only show relevant information.

    Usage Example:

    Temperature Instrument with minimum value 0, maximum 125, current value 22 and units are Celsius:

    Instrument tempgauge = new RangeInstrument(0,125,22,"Celsius","C");

    Volt Meter Example:

    Instrument voltmeter = new RangeInstrument(10,14,12,"Volts", "V");

    Useful Methods include:

    getPercentage() Returns the current value - as a percentage of the range

    getPercentageString() Returns the current value - as a percentage of the range, with a % symbol and in string format

    toString() Returns a 10char sting filled proportionally with the percentage state of the instrument. e.g. 75% of range is returned as *******---

      • RangeInstrument

        public RangeInstrument(int minimum,
                       int maximum,
                       int initial,
                       String unit,
                       String unitSymbol,
                       int warning,
                       boolean maxWarning)
        Constructs an instrument that displays current value, minimum and maximum value of the range are both defined. An initial display value is defined for instrument initialisation before it has received a value update. Unit name and symbol are defined. A warning set point and behaviour (minimum or maximum warning) is also defined.
        Parameters:
        minimum - the minimum display range of this instrument
        maximum - the maximum display range of this instrument
        initial - the starting display value for this instrument
        unit - the name of the units this instrument is displaying
        unitSymbol - the symbol or abbreviation for the units this instrument is displaying
        warning - the value at which the instrument will display a warning
        maxWarning - True if warning is maximum, False to use warning as a minimum
